{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612473"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:23:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:23:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16278"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16278"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.03,0.31,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8969"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74634"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8969"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60128"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"9633"},{"type":"tags","id":"10216"},{"type":"tags","id":"10676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21344"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21351"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74634"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDelayed puberty is a common concern in adolescent medicine. Various clinical and radiological features help distinguish pathological from constitutional delay.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical skeletal findings in delayed puberty?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bone age delayed more than two standard deviations from chronological age","Advanced bone age with normal growth velocity","Normal bone age with decreased growth velocity","Accelerated growth velocity for bone age","Normal bone age with accelerated growth velocity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn delayed puberty, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone age is typically delayed more than two standard deviations from chronological age\u003C/strong\u003E. This delay in skeletal maturation is particularly characteristic of constitutional delay of growth and puberty, the most common cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvanced bone age with normal growth velocity\u003C/strong\u003E - Advanced bone age is more typical of precocious rather than delayed puberty\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal bone age with decreased growth velocity\u003C/strong\u003E - Both bone age and growth velocity are typically delayed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccelerated growth velocity for bone age\u003C/strong\u003E - Growth velocity is typically decreased relative to chronological age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal bone age with accelerated growth velocity\u003C/strong\u003E - Neither finding is consistent with delayed puberty\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrowth velocity is typically low when compared to chronological age but may be appropriate for bone age. The delayed skeletal maturation allows for continued growth potential once puberty eventually begins.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Delayed puberty is defined as absence of secondary sexual characteristics by age 13 in girls or age 14 in boys.","Delayed puberty is associated with delayed skeletal maturation and reduced growth velocity relative to chronological age.","Bone age is typically delayed by more than two standard deviations from chronological age in constitutional delay of growth and puberty."],"references":["Elhakeem A, Frysz M, Tilling K, Tobias JH, Lawlor DA. Association Between Age at Puberty and Bone Accrual From 10 to 25 Years of Age. JAMA Netw Open. 2019 Aug 2;2(8):e198918. doi: 10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2019.8918. PMID: 31397863; PMCID: PMC6692837","Gilsanz V, Chalfant J, Kalkwarf H, Zemel B, Lappe J, Oberfield S, Shepherd J, Wren T, Winer K. Age at onset of puberty predicts bone mass in young adulthood. J Pediatr. 2011 Jan;158(1):100-5, 105.e1-2. doi: 10.1016/j.jpeds.2010.06.054. Epub 2010 Aug 24. PMID: 20797727; PMCID: PMC4767165","Cousminer DL, Mitchell JA, Chesi A, Roy SM, Kalkwarf HJ, Lappe JM, Gilsanz V, Oberfield SE, Shepherd JA, Kelly A, McCormack SE, Voight BF, Zemel BS, Grant SF. Genetically Determined Later Puberty Impacts Lowered Bone Mineral Density in Childhood and Adulthood. J Bone Miner Res. 2018 Mar;33(3):430-436. doi: 10.1002/jbmr.3320. Epub 2017 Nov 17. PMID: 29068475; PMCID: PMC5839967","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60128"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16278"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60128"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T23:25:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T00:01:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8969"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74634"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Pae